language is almost identical to <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST9-11-43" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0c9374627fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 9-11-43(c)</cite.query> except that the federal rules relate only to the law of a foreign country.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Pursuant to <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS1507" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c93c2807fc011ea988285db8533e975">44 U.S.C.A. § 1507</cite.query>, courts are to judicially notice the contents of the Federal Register. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS1510" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c93c2817fc011ea988285db8533e975">44 U.S.C.A. § 1510</cite.query> does not reference judicial notice in providing for the Code of Federal Regulations, but that material appeared in the Federal Register, so the same statement would apply.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Although there is no clear statement that <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS1507" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c965a937fc011ea988285db8533e975">§ 1507</cite.query> applies to state courts, a few cases have taken judicial notice of the Federal Register. <eos/><bos/>For example, in <ital><cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-serial-number="1965125714" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RS" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0c965a927fc011ea988285db8533e975">Sims v. Southern Bell Telephone and Telegraph Co.</cite.query>, Inc.</ital>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3790c807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals held that a court would not take judicial notice of tariffs filed with the Federal Communications Commission. <eos/><bos/>The court stated that, under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS307" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c976c007fc011ea988285db8533e975">44 U.S.C.A. §§ 307</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS311" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c976c017fc011ea988285db8533e975">311</cite.query> [now <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS1507" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c976c027fc011ea988285db8533e975">44 U.S.C.A. §§ 1507</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS1510" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c976c037fc011ea988285db8533e975">1510</cite.query>], they were required to take judicial notice of the Federal Register and the Code of Federal Regulations.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic378e5707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-serial-number="1885180033" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I0c92ff327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Lamar v. Micou, 114 U.S. 218, 5 S. Ct. 857, 29 L. Ed. 94 (1885)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3790c807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-serial-number="1965125714" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0c96f6d27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Sims v. Southern Bell Tel. &amp; Tel. Co., 111 Ga. App. 363, 141 S.E.2d 788 (1965)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-serial-number="1984142731" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0c96f6d57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ford Motor Co. v. Stubblefield, 171 Ga. App. 331, 319 S.E.2d 470 (1984)</cite.query>, held that, under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017105" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS2112" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I0c96f6d67fc011ea988285db8533e975">44 U.S.C.A. § 2112(b)</cite.query> the court was required to take judicial notice of the official seal of the National Archives of the United States.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 6:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
